by Alfonso Sanchez¶

The dataset used for this project is related with results from the 2012 pisa exam. The dataset is composed by results for students from OCDE countries.

This project is focused on the performance of students from Japan, the United Kingdom and Mexico, since are countries with results above the average, with average results and with results below the average, respectively. The objective of this project is to understand the factors related with the performance of students when taking the pisa exam.

Assessing the data¶

Presence of missing or undefined values in the dataset, proportion of missing values on each of the dataset columns:

In [4]:
PlotNullCols(pisa, 7)

Finding nan patterns among columns and rows of the dataset:

In [5]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18,7))  
sns.heatmap(pisa.isnull(), cbar=False,cmap="Blues");

It can be observed in the previous figure that there are different behaviors of nan values. Then, it will be difficult to drop all nan values, given that there exists the possibility to drop all rows of the generated dataset. Removing columns of rows with enough nan values to be considered outliers will only clean a small proportion of the nan values. As result, it was concluded to implement the following steps in order to analyze the generated dataset:

  • Generate subsets to study different features of interest related with the performances of the students. This, to analyze more features, while reducing the effects of the nan values present.

  • Reduce the amount of nan values on the created datasets.

  • Compare the proportion of information for each of the selected countries. It needs to be similar for each of the selected countries in all the created datasets.

  • Assure that the pisa exam results maintain the same behavior in all the created datasets. Otherwise, the analysis wont be possible.

  • Re-encode non-numerical variables.

  • Create dictionaries to encode or decode features of interest.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset provided was divided into four new datasets to deal with the missing and unknown values, avoiding the dropping of important features. Each of the generated datasets contains different features of interest, each of them represents specific students characteristics that help to understand their performances during the pisa test. The datasets are composed by the information of only three countries, as explained next.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The dataframe contains information related with OCDE countries, however, this analysis is based only on three of them. The selected countries are Japan, the United Kingdom and Mexico, countries selected to represent students with results above the average, with average results and with results below the average, respectively. The goal of this analysis is to understand the variables that affect the students performances when taking the PISA exam.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features in the datasets that can help to support the analysis are those related with the students genders, their parents occupations and education, the school attendance, the use of tools such calculators and the time used to study outside the school. The objective is to relate these features with the students performances during the PISA exam, comparing differences between the selected countries.

In [28]:
#Plotting distributions for the student's time spent studying doing with their parents
PlotDistHist(pisaC, 'ST57Q05', names, bins, DictCols['ST57Q05'], Figsize=(13,4), orient='h')

The previous figure presents an unusual behaviour for a specific value, for each of the selected countries. Most of the students spent cero hours studying with their parents. After a small research, it was found that the cero value is associated by the OCDE with missing or unknow values for this feature. Therefore, is required to re-encode these values as nan:

In [29]:
pisaC2 = pisaC.copy()
pisaC2.ST57Q05.replace(0, np.nan, inplace=True)
PlotDistHist(pisaC2, 'ST57Q05', names, bins, DictCols['ST57Q05'], Figsize=(13,4), orient='h')

The re-encoded distributions let us see that the amount of time students spent with their parents studying is not a factor to get better performances in the pisa exam, as Japan is the most successful country in the pisa exams with less hours.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most transformations were implemented in the wrangling section. However, in order to increase the understanding of the presented graphics some values were mapped using dictionaries generated in the wrangling section. Nonetheless, most distributions do not present any observable outliers, and the ones observable do not affect the main understanding of the distributions, as was the case for the study time outside the school. At the end of the previous analysis, it was concluded that the variables of interest are the parents higher ISCED educations, the use of calculators, and the age when the students started their ISCED 1 education.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Most of the unusual distributions were removed in the previous section. However, it was not considered predefined codes used by the OCDE to represent missing or unknown values for the ST57Q05 feature. The effect of this was that most students, for each of the countries of interest, studied cero hours with their parents. The predefined code for missing values is cero. Then, after re-encoded the missing values as nan values it was possible to understand the students behaviours when studying with their parents.

Thus, the performance of the students when taking the pisa exam do not vary too much depending on the students gender.

sns.heatmap(CNTRes.corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.2f', cmap = pal, center = 0, linewidths=.5)
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
plt.yticks(rotation=0);

This figure proves the previous conclusions. There exist high correlations among results for the different sections of the pisa exam from students of the same country, while results obtained from students of different countries are almost uncorrelated. Additionally, results obtained from Japanese and British students are highly correlated for the different sections of the pisa exam. On the other hand, obtained results from Mexican students between the different sections of the pisa exam are less correlated.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Results obtained from students of the same country are highly correlated, while results among students of different countries are not, even when the results compared are from the same section of the pisa exam. This remarks differences in the way education is provided on each of the mentioned countries.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The most surprised interactions were the higher correlation among results obtained from Japanese and British students when solving the different sections of the pisa exam when compared with the Mexican students. This can be related with many unconsidered variables, but there exists the possibility that Mexican education is just not as good as the education provided in Japan or in the United Kingdom, especially when observed that many factors that affect students from the three countries affect them in similar proportions, as shown in the univariate section.
